<div id="tl" class="u-sec"><span class="u-sec-text">The timeline — myth vs. record</span></div>

<div class="u-timeline">

  <div class="u-era">
    <div class="u-era-head" onclick="tog(this)">
      <div class="u-era-left">
        <div class="u-era-period">Pre-1492</div>
        <div class="u-era-title">Before European contact <span class="u-era-tag tag-gap">Skipped entirely</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="u-era-arrow">▾</div>
    </div>
    <div class="u-era-body">
      <div class="u-col u-col-myth"><span class="u-col-badge badge-myth">What you were taught</span><p>Vague mention of "Indians" on the land. No nations, no names, no governance. The textbook story begins when Europeans arrive.</p></div>
      <div class="u-col u-col-reality"><span class="u-col-badge badge-real">What the record shows</span><p>Over <strong>500 distinct nations</strong> with sophisticated governments, trade networks, agriculture, and cities. The Haudenosaunee Confederacy's democratic structure directly influenced the U.S. Constitution. These were not peoples awaiting civilization — they <em>were</em> civilization.</p></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="u-era">
    <div class="u-era-head" onclick="tog(this)">
      <div class="u-era-left">
        <div class="u-era-period">1490s</div>
        <div class="u-era-title">Columbus and "discovery" <span class="u-era-tag tag-myth">Actively distorted</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="u-era-arrow">▾</div>
    </div>
    <div class="u-era-body">
      <div class="u-col u-col-myth"><span class="u-col-badge badge-myth">What you were taught</span><p><em>"In 1492, Columbus sailed the ocean blue."</em> A brave explorer who discovered America. Columbus Day was a national celebration of his courage and vision.</p></div>
      <div class="u-col u-col-reality"><span class="u-col-badge badge-real">What the record shows</span><p>Columbus never set foot in the continental United States. He initiated <strong>forced labor, mutilation, and genocide</strong> of the Taíno people. Norse explorer Leif Erikson reached the Americas centuries earlier. Tens of millions of people already lived here — there was nothing to "discover."</p></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="u-era">
    <div class="u-era-head" onclick="tog(this)">
      <div class="u-era-left">
        <div class="u-era-period">1620s</div>
        <div class="u-era-title">Pilgrims and Thanksgiving <span class="u-era-tag tag-myth">Actively distorted</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="u-era-arrow">▾</div>
    </div>
    <div class="u-era-body">
      <div class="u-col u-col-myth"><span class="u-col-badge badge-myth">What you were taught</span><p>Students dressed as Pilgrims and Indians to share a peaceful harvest meal. A story of friendship, gratitude, and cooperation between two peoples starting fresh.</p></div>
      <div class="u-col u-col-reality"><span class="u-col-badge badge-real">What the record shows</span><p>European disease had already killed up to <strong>90% of coastal New England's Indigenous population</strong> before the Pilgrims arrived. King Philip's War (1675–76) devastated northeastern nations within a generation. The land the Pilgrims "settled" had been emptied by epidemic.</p></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="u-era">
    <div class="u-era-head" onclick="tog(this)">
      <div class="u-era-left">
        <div class="u-era-period">1800s</div>
        <div class="u-era-title">Manifest Destiny <span class="u-era-tag tag-myth">Actively distorted</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="u-era-arrow">▾</div>
    </div>
    <div class="u-era-body">
      <div class="u-col u-col-myth"><span class="u-col-badge badge-myth">What you were taught</span><p>A patriotic, God-given mission to expand the nation from sea to sea. Lessons focused on settler courage and the hardships <em>they</em> endured crossing the frontier.</p></div>
      <div class="u-col u-col-reality"><span class="u-col-badge badge-real">What the record shows</span><p>An ideology of <strong>white supremacy and land seizure</strong>. It justified systematic displacement, starvation campaigns, and destruction of entire villages — actions meeting the modern legal definition of ethnic cleansing.</p></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="u-era">
    <div class="u-era-head" onclick="tog(this)">
      <div class="u-era-left">
        <div class="u-era-period">1830s</div>
        <div class="u-era-title">Trail of Tears <span class="u-era-tag tag-min">Minimized</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="u-era-arrow">▾</div>
    </div>
    <div class="u-era-body">
      <div class="u-col u-col-myth"><span class="u-col-badge badge-myth">What you were taught</span><p>A "difficult decision" by Andrew Jackson to relocate Native tribes. Covered briefly and framed as regrettable — rarely as a moral atrocity or deliberate cruelty.</p></div>
      <div class="u-col u-col-reality"><span class="u-col-badge badge-real">What the record shows</span><p>A <strong>deliberate federal act of ethnic cleansing</strong>. The Indian Removal Act displaced the Cherokee, Choctaw, Creek, Chickasaw, and Seminole nations. Thousands died on forced marches. The Cherokee called it <em>Nunna daul Tsuny</em> — "the trail where they cried."</p></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="u-era">
    <div class="u-era-head" onclick="tog(this)">
      <div class="u-era-left">
        <div class="u-era-period">1819–1978</div>
        <div class="u-era-title">Federal Indian boarding schools <span class="u-era-tag tag-gap">Completely absent</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="u-era-arrow">▾</div>
    </div>
    <div class="u-era-body">
      <div class="u-col u-col-myth"><span class="u-col-badge badge-myth">What you were taught</span><p>Nothing. This 150-year chapter is absent from most K-12 curricula. Most students graduate without ever hearing about it.</p></div>
      <div class="u-col u-col-reality"><span class="u-col-badge badge-real">What the record shows</span><p>The U.S. government forcibly removed Native children and sent them to <strong>417 documented boarding schools</strong> to eliminate Indigenous identity. Hair cut off. Names replaced. Languages forbidden. Official motto: <em>"Kill the Indian, save the man."</em> Intergenerational trauma continues today.</p></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="u-era">
    <div class="u-era-head" onclick="tog(this)">
      <div class="u-era-left">
        <div class="u-era-period">1900s+</div>
        <div class="u-era-title">The 20th century and beyond <span class="u-era-tag tag-gap">Completely absent</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="u-era-arrow">▾</div>
    </div>
    <div class="u-era-body">
      <div class="u-col u-col-myth"><span class="u-col-badge badge-myth">What you were taught</span><p>Nothing. The textbook narrative ends in the 1890s — implying, without saying it, that Native peoples ceased to exist or ceased to matter.</p></div>
      <div class="u-col u-col-reality"><span class="u-col-badge badge-real">What the record shows</span><p>The 20th century brought <strong>forced sterilizations</strong>, termination policies, and urban relocation programs. It also brought the American Indian Movement, Alcatraz, and the Self-Determination Act. Native Americans didn't receive citizenship until <strong>1924</strong> and voting rights were suppressed into the 1960s.</p></div>
    </div>
  </div>

</div>

