<div id="myths" class="u-sec" style="margin-top:1.5rem"><span class="u-sec-text">Five myths you probably still believe</span></div>
<div class="u-myths-section">
  <div class="u-myths-grid">
    <div class="u-myth-card"><div class="u-myth-num">01</div><div class="u-myth-title">Native Americans are a people of the past</div><p class="u-myth-body">There are 574 federally recognized tribal nations in the U.S. today. Native people are alive, governing, and fighting for their rights — right now.</p></div>
    <div class="u-myth-card"><div class="u-myth-num">02</div><div class="u-myth-title">Columbus discovered America</div><p class="u-myth-body">Tens of millions of people already lived here. Columbus initiated genocide in the Caribbean. That's not discovery — it's invasion.</p></div>
    <div class="u-myth-card"><div class="u-myth-num">03</div><div class="u-myth-title">Thanksgiving was a friendly celebration</div><p class="u-myth-body">The "first Thanksgiving" narrative ignores the epidemic that had already emptied the region and the violent wars that followed within a single generation.</p></div>
    <div class="u-myth-card"><div class="u-myth-num">04</div><div class="u-myth-title">Manifest Destiny was about progress</div><p class="u-myth-body">It was a racial ideology. Expanding the United States required the elimination — through removal, starvation, and massacre — of the people already there.</p></div>
    <div class="u-myth-card"><div class="u-myth-num">05</div><div class="u-myth-title">The boarding schools were just schools</div><p class="u-myth-body">They were institutions of cultural erasure. Children were beaten for speaking their languages. Thousands died. The last one didn't close until 1978.</p></div>
    <div class="u-myth-card" style="border-color:rgba(176,58,26,.3);background:var(--rust-soft)">
      <div class="u-myth-num" style="color:var(--rust);opacity:1">?</div>
      <div class="u-myth-title" style="color:var(--rust)">What else weren't you told?</div>
      <p class="u-myth-body">This covers a fraction of what was left out. Read the sources. Keep asking questions your textbook never did.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div id="today" class="u-sec" style="margin-top:0.5rem"><span class="u-sec-text">Native Americans today — still here</span></div>
<div class="u-today-section">
  <div class="u-today-grid">
    <div class="u-today-cell"><div class="u-today-head">574 sovereign nations</div><p>Federally recognized tribal governments exist across the U.S., each with their own laws and leadership. Tribes are not ethnic groups — they are <strong>governments</strong>.</p></div>
    <div class="u-today-cell"><div class="u-today-head">Treaties still being broken</div><p>The U.S. signed hundreds of treaties with Native nations. <strong>Not a single one has been fully honored.</strong> Disputes over land, water, and sovereignty continue in federal court today.</p></div>
    <div class="u-today-cell"><div class="u-today-head">Language and culture revival</div><p>Dozens of nations are reclaiming languages that boarding schools tried to destroy — through immersion schools, elder-led programs, and community archives.</p></div>
    <div class="u-today-cell"><div class="u-today-head">The education gap</div><p>Native students have the <strong>lowest graduation and college enrollment rates</strong> in the country. This is the direct result of a century of dispossession, underfunding, and erasure from the curriculum.</p></div>
  </div>
</div>

